metadata.name: Sketching #505
metadata.description:
Rules : 
  1. Start with either a line or a circle from a number of random points in the space.
  2. A line can only spawn a circle at the end. 
  3. A circle can spawn both lines and circles before it completes the full circle.
  4. A circle can sometimes spawn an inner circle.
  5. Smaller elements will spawn randomly along with the lines.

This was inspired by the patterns in Marvel's movie : Eternals. I enjoyed the line growing animation with basic geometry ( line and circle ). Combining this with the rules It generates interesting results.

To add more variety to the rendering, I've added the dash lines in instead of only solid lines. Also the 'lines' consist of thousands of small dots to give it randomness and a bit of texture feeling.

metadata.name: Colorfall #30
metadata.description:
My first attempt at a generative NFT. This started with an idea to create a grid of diagonal lines with the basic line function of p5js. I had discarded this idea until my friend said it looked like a waterfall of colors and he liked it, so I decided to mint it. After tweaking some parameters like colors and line thickness it produced some nice outputs.

I hope you will enjoy it. Free mint(unless you cant wait and want to pay =) plus 25% royalties for minters.

reserves for the collectors of my testnft on objkt, my friend CampendonkP and a few artists who I remembered who did free mints, like punevyr and JohnRising.

The Pandora generative series has the same qualities as the mythological figure. Able to adopt many different shapes, a wide variety of colors and styles, all created from simple rules.

metadata.name: Explorations I #30
metadata.description:
Exploring board game layouts to produce generative art.

When the board is generated, several pieces are chosen not to have a hex field. Then, each of those are connected by a line.

- A selection of 8 different palettes, with various rarity
- Property 'Thick Lines' that is a Yes/No, and controls the way the lines are drawn that connect the board pieces that don't have a hex
- Property 'Circles' that is a Yes/No, and controls whether circles are drawn in the board pieces that don't have a hex

Due to the size of the board and the feature properties, a lot of varied outputs can be minted.

Price: 0.88 tez
Editions: 128
Creator: 0xMartinS
Twitter: https://twitter.com/0xMartinS

Press 's' on the keyboard to capture an image and download.

metadata.name: Urban Inception Redux #503
metadata.description:
Urban Inception Redux borrows from the original Circle City project and goes bigger, 6x bigger to be exact, and adds a whole new alternate reality, more rings, and a new skew potential. 

PLEASE BE PATIENT - This project has a lot of computations and may take a minute or two to render. 

This project creates a 12 layer composition that can be exported as an SVG and plotted or used to cut a physical out of wood or acrylic using a laser. With each layer being a single contiguous element. 

More info about the project and physicals can be found at: 
https://alleditions.art/p/urban-inception-redux

Shift P - Export a PNG
Shift S - Export an SVG
Shift E - explode the layers

metadata.name: Incorporeal Spaces #3
metadata.description:
In this shader-based generative system each pixel in the image figures out its own color according to the relative distances to a series of points. The points themselves are not visible, but each of them has a color assigned. As they move in space to form different geometric arrangements, their influence on the surrounding pixels creates new color configurations.

This is, at its core, an expansion on the idea of Voronoi tessellations (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Voronoi_diagram). In classic Voronoi, each pixel would just take the color of the closest point. In this system, the color of each pixel is the average, weighted by distance, of the closest N-points (this is the “range”), optionally skipping some at the beginning (this is the “offset”).

This is a dynamic work that generates endless new configurations and never repeats itself. The sequence of configurations, as well as the color palette (out of 10 possible) is unique to each edition. 

This is a new instance of a system that was initially developed in Processing in year 2015. Captures of the original work can still be seen at https://flickr.com/photos/solaas/albums/72157657608772501/with/20166059054/

Controls:
[Click or tap] to randomly change range and offset
[Space] to play/pause
[s] to download capture
[f] to toggle fullscreen

Coded in JavaScript and GLSL, using the open-source libraries p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Perpetual Oscillations  #49
metadata.description:
Planes expand and contract over time in different rhythms. 

Display notes:
The work is intended to be viewed running live in the browser, and there is no set aspect ratio. The viewer is invited to explore the space and choose their viewpoint. 

Controls:
Left-clicking and dragging - rotate around the center 
right-clicking and dragging - pan around the space 
Scrolling - zoom in and out 
Press b - b-side 
Press o - go back to the origin 
Press 1 to 3 - change the pixel density
Adjusting pixel density or changing the screen size will bring you back to the origin. 

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

Made with p5.js
